# =====================================================================
#  Environment configuration
#
#  Copy this file to ".env" and fill in the values:   cp .env.example .env
#
#  Every variable below shows what it is, an Example, and the Best
#  practice where it matters. Variables are ordered most-needed first:
#  the two REQUIRED ones are at the top, then OPTIONAL ones from
#  most-likely to least-likely to need.
# =====================================================================


# REQUIRED  -  Telegram bot token from @BotFather.
# The bot will not start without it. Treat it like a password.
# Example:  BOT_TOKEN="123456789:AAFakeExampleTokenFromBotFather_xxx"
BOT_TOKEN=""


# REQUIRED  -  The channel the bot posts to.
# The bot will not start without it. The bot account must first be added
# to the channel as an admin with BOTH the "Post messages" and the
# "Delete messages" permissions (the second is for the
# replace-on-next-fire cleanup of repeating azkar; see CLAUDE.md).
#
# Two accepted forms:
#   * Numeric id  ->  CHANNEL_CHAT_ID="-1001234567890"   (recommended)
#   * @username   ->  CHANNEL_CHAT_ID="@mychannel"
#
# Best practice: use the numeric id. It never changes, even if you later
# rename the channel's public @username, so posting can never break that
# way. To find it, forward any channel message to @username_to_id_bot.
#
# Do NOT put a https://t.me/... link here. Telegram rejects a URL as a
# chat id and posting would fail. The public link goes in the next
# variable instead.
# Example:  CHANNEL_CHAT_ID="-1001234567890"
CHANNEL_CHAT_ID=""


# OPTIONAL  -  The channel's public share link.
# Used ONLY to show a tap-through link in the /start reply. It is kept
# separate from CHANNEL_CHAT_ID on purpose: posting always uses the
# stable id above, so this cosmetic link can never break posting.
#
# Best practice: paste the exact link you share with people, i.e. the
# full https form. (An "@username" or "t.me/..." value also works; all
# of them resolve to the same https://t.me/... link.)
#
# Leave empty for a private channel (it has no public link). You can
# also leave it empty if CHANNEL_CHAT_ID is an @username, because the
# link is then derived from it automatically.
# Example:  CHANNEL_PUBLIC_URL="https://t.me/yourchannel"
CHANNEL_PUBLIC_URL=""


# OPTIONAL  -  Timezone for every cron schedule in src/schedules.ts.
# If empty the code falls back to UTC, which is rarely what you want, so
# set this to your audience's timezone. Use a valid IANA tz name.
# Best practice: keep all post times at 02:00 or later (see CLAUDE.md:
# the once-a-year DST gap can silently drop a job).
# Example:  TZ_NAME="Africa/Cairo"   (others: "Europe/London", "Asia/Riyadh")
TZ_NAME="Africa/Cairo"


# OPTIONAL  -  Your numeric Telegram user id. Enables the /admin_*
# commands (health check, manual send) for that one user, in a private
# chat with the bot only. Leave empty to disable all admin commands.
# Get your id by messaging @userinfobot on Telegram.
# Example:  ADMIN_TELEGRAM_ID="123456789"
ADMIN_TELEGRAM_ID=""


# OPTIONAL  -  Path to the tiny JSON pointer file used by the bot to
# remember the last message_id it posted for each message-schedule, so
# the replace-on-next-fire delete survives a process restart.
#
# Not a database — same conceptual weight as this .env file. Losing it
# just means each schedule leaks one stale message until the next
# cycle. On ephemeral hosts (no persistent disk) that is the steady
# state; on hosts with a persistent disk it survives restarts.
#
# Leave empty for the default ./data/last-message-ids.json (fine for
# almost everyone). Set this only if you need a different location,
# e.g. a mounted volume on your host.
# Example:  STATE_FILE="./data/last-message-ids.json"
STATE_FILE=""


# OPTIONAL  -  Runtime mode. Set to "production" on a hosted deploy
# (this quietens debug logs). Anything else is treated as development.
# Example:  NODE_ENV="production"
NODE_ENV="development"


# OPTIONAL  -  HTTP port for the /health endpoint. Defaults to 8080.
# Many hosts inject their own PORT automatically, so you usually leave
# this empty. A blank or invalid value safely falls back to 8080.
# Example:  PORT="8080"
PORT=""
